Durban - King Goodwill Zwelithini is to be conferred an honorary doctorate by the University of Zululand in recognition of his humanitarian work.

The honourary doctorate in social work, will be bestowed on the King on May 4, for his; "far reaching vision and vital contribution in combating social ills amongst the youth and the society at large," read a statement from the university. ADVERTISINGinRead invented by Teads

As the 8th Zulu monarch, the King is also also the chairman of the Ingonyama Trust, a corporate entity established to administer the land traditionally owned by the king for the benefit, material welfare and social well-being of the Zulu nation.

UniZulu Vice-Chancellor Prof Xoliswa Mtose said said the university was delighted to recognise the King who had founded the Bayethe Trust Foundation. 

The foundation's chief executive, Rhana Naicker, said the King was humbled by the gesture saying it was important to maintain the strong links with UniZulu, as a knowledge hub. “We have high expectations of the university to contribute to the education of our people and to advance research and innovation in ways that will support our aspirations and benefit our communities. This honour recognises our partnership and is a testimony of
Ubuntu  concept that the King lives and breath,” said Naicker. 

The honourary doctorate will be conferred at a special graduation ceremony at the University’s KwaDlangezwa campus. 
